               <p>MARY NIBLETT. I am <rs id="t18300527-227-viclabel1199" type="occupation">single</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-227-victim1858 t18300527-227-viclabel1199"></join>; the prisoner was in my employ as a <rs id="t18300527-227-deflabel1200" type="occupation">day worker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-227-defend1856 t18300527-227-deflabel1200"></join> - I live in <placeName id="t18300527-227-crimeloc1201">Dorset-street, Salisbury-square</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-227-crimeloc1201" type="placeName" value="Dorset-street, Salisbury-square"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300527-227-crimeloc1201" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-227-off1197 t18300527-227-crimeloc1201"></join>, and am a <rs id="t18300527-227-viclabel1202" type="occupation">dress-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300527-227-victim1858 t18300527-227-viclabel1202"></join> - she lived three weeks or a month with me. I missed this property on Tuesday last - I at first suspected a servant, whom I had parted with, and from her confession I suspected the prisoner; I charged her with it on Friday, and said it would be better to confess.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-227-person1859">
                  WILLIAM 
                  IVEY
               <interp inst="t18300527-227-person1859" type="surname" value="IVEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-227-person1859" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-227-person1859" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a shopman to Mr. Reeves, of Snow-hill. This silk was pawned by the prisoner on the 24th of May - she came again on the Friday, and said she had lost the duplicate, would I let her have it; I said not without an affidavit, and it was then too late to get one.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I did not intend to keep it - she promised if I would own it. she would not hurt me, and gave me till Saturday to redeem it.</p>
               <p>MARY NIBLETT. I did not give her any stated time.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 27.</p>
